Did Level of Prior Medical Care Correlate with Health Outcomes in the Covid-19 Pandemic¶

Sam Kevy, 917191015

Introduction¶

This report utilized the WHO database tracking all cases of Covid-19 in every country through out the world. This dataset was combined with data tracking the average number of times an individual recieved medical care (ie saw a doctor) per year for 41 countries. In addition each countries GDP (Gross Domestic Product) was included in the data set. This dataset was used to answer the following question of interest: Did the the level of healthcare citizens recieved prior to the Covid-19 pandemic (as measured by number of Dr. Visits), in addition to the GDP of said country have an effect on the number of cumulative deaths per capita in the year 2020 that a country suffered?

Background¶

Covid-19 is a highly transmissable virus which originated in December of 2019 in Wuhan China. It quickly spread around the globe, infecting around 420 million people in just over 2 years, killing 5.86 million. The elderly, and those with pre-existing conditions and auto-immune issues have been most at risk of death, as well as other significant ailements.

Summary Statistics¶

For the purpose of this analysis, we will only examine Covid-19 cases in the year 2020. There were 55,471,813 global cases in 2020, 1,298,019 deaths, with a case mortality rate of 0.023 or 2.3%.

Inferential Analysis¶

To analyze the question of interest, we'll linear regression following the model yi=β0+x1β1+x2β2+ β3X1X2 +ϵi where B0 represents the intercept, B1 the coefficient of X1 number of medical visits, B2 the coefficient of X2 GDP and B3 the coefficient of the interaction of X1 and X2, the relationship between number of medical appointments and country GDP.

Need to add: Assumptions for model Is this the best model?

This model allows us to complete a F-hypothesis testing, which allows us to reject any linear correlation between deaths per capita, number of medical visits and GDP.

Fitting Model¶

Once fitted, the linear regression model shows that there is no linear correlation between deaths per capita, number of medical visits and GDP. Following the null hypothesis that B1=B2=B3=0 and the alternative hypothesis that B1,B2, and B3 do not equal zero , we fail to reject the null hypothesis, as the p-value are all greater than the selected significane level of 0.05.

However, when we look for linear correlation between cases per capita, number of medical visits and GDP, following the null hypothesis that B1=B2=B3=0 and the alternative hypothesis that B1,B2, and B3 do not equal zero, we reject the null hypothesis that B2 and B3=0. This is because the p-values here are smaller than 0.05

Sensitivity Analysis¶

For the model contain deaths per capita, we can see significant clear deviation from the ideal horizontal band, indicating that the variance of errors is not equal. The normal qq plot, does indicate that the variance of errors follows a relatively normal distribution.

The same can be said for the model containing cases per capita, which puts our rejecting of the null hypothesis into question.

Using models that acount for non-constant residuals¶

To do this, we will use functions from the nlme package that is included with the base installation of R. The workhorse function is gls, which stands for “generalized least squares”. We use it just as we would the lm function, except we also use the weights argument along with a handful of variance functions. Let’s demonstrate with an example.

Below we fit the “correct” model to our data that exhibited non-constant variance. We load the nlme package so we can use the gls function1. We specify the model syntax as before, y ~ x. Then we use the weights argument to specify the variance function, in this case varFixed, also part of the nlme package. This says our variance function has no parameters and a single covariate, x, which is precisely how we generated the data. The syntax, ~x, is a one-sided formula that can be read as “model variance as a function of x.”

Conclusion¶

To conclude, we fail to find any statistically significant relationship between cases and deaths per capita and number of medical visists per year and GDP. There was significant deviation among residuals indicating that a better fitting regression model should be utilized. It is quite likely that other factors, like governental and societal response dictated case rate and death outcomes, instead of how accesible medical care was pre-pandemic or even the GDP of a particular country. A possible future study could investigate the relationship between cases/deaths per capita and the type of government, as more authoritarian governments might have reduced cases by suspending some civil liberties, which is less possible in democracies.
